\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well my name is William Henry Page.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 My present address is Y Gorlan, 50, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Maesteg Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Cwmfelin, Maestag.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And you are married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And the year of marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 1945.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Your year of birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 September the twenty-fifth, 1898.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 At Llangynwyd Village. Maesteg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 I lived - eleven years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Where did you live then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Went from there - down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Maesteg Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Cwmfelin, number fifty-nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember why you moved then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Why we moved? Well, the reason why we moved, the house then was - we as children had grown up, and my brother was very interested in music, in fact he was the organist of the church and a conductor, and we were all a musical family. My grandmother,
 she was a presenter up at the church. And - we are a musical family back for four or five generations, well he came down and - we thought the house would be a little bit bigger than that cottage and that's why we came to Maesteg Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Then you moved them did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 To Nantyfyllon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 That was in 1920?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Why did you move to Nantyfyllon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well then I got married you see. And - I had - been - went - I cheated my age, during the first world war, and I joined the Army. And of cou
rse - I was in this country six weeks. They were supposed to have done my training, there was a recall and I went - I was drafted out to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, in six weeks. And from there I came back - in 1919. But I was in - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose} in the Army of Occupation for about six to seven months, on the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}Rhine{\*\xmlclose}. Came back then because - there was a call then for colliers to come back to the mine, and they were the first people - that they'd give a - privilege to come home because of the big call for miners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 So you came back then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
I come back then. And as you say, as I just said, I got married then, and I lived in Nantyfyllon for a while. Then I moved from there back to where I'm living now and that is 58 Maesteg Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Why did you move from Nantyfyllon to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Maesteg Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well I came here because - to get a house of our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 I have - one brother and two sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Can you remember when they were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes. My brother was born in 1892. And - next
 to him was my sister, she was born in 1895. And it happened to be in the same day - same day, and the same month, in April. Then - I was born in 1898. My younger sister in 1904.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How old was your father when you were born? I think we worked it out tha
t he was 30?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Thirty, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Where did your father come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
He was born in Llangynwyd Village, there he was born, and there he lived until we moved down - to Maesteg Road, number 59, and there he died at the age of ninety.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What were his jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
He was a miner. Worked underground. All the days of his life. He started to work when he was twelve years of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did he have any other job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No other job at all, only a miner, that was sufficient in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did he do any casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No, not any - no, no, no casual jobs in fact they couldn't very well do it in those days because - the hours on the - in - in the mine then, underground as we term it, were thirteen hours a day, and that was Saturday and eve
ry day of course. The only day off was on Sunday, and during the winter months they never seen daylight only on Saturday afternoon, and Sunday. Therefore they didn't have much time to do any other job, other than of course - in the garden. We had to prepa
r
e that. Because that - was part of our living. And - during the time we were living there, all the people, they were poor people in that village then, quite a number of them lived off we termed then as the Barish, they call it - subsistence today. But owi
n
g they had - that dignity about them they would not go and have any charity, they'd rather work for it. And my mother and many of them, they used to go around the farms, and - she had a - a quilting frame, and she used to do - quilting, just for a few shi
llings around the farms and at home, rather than go and ask for any Parish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Why do you think they felt like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Their - dignity, they had that dignity about them, what is - a great difference, it's gone from one extreme to the other today. The 
other way, they wear their fur coats to go and get it today, but in those days, it would be very very hard and pushed - very very hard, before they'd go, they'd rather work. Remember my mother then used to go - round the farms and - work all day, just pat
ching the clothes of the farmers, just for few shillings and perhaps - a piece of bacon. Something like that. That's how they used to live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember her doing that when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 I do. I do, I can see the frame now. In the little ro
om. With her - with her quilting going on. Handwork every bit of it. And after it was completed it was a pleasure to see it and it would last for years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No, not until - he - became too old
 to work. In those days - they had - they could work - until they were seventy years of age. But my grandfather, he would not say - he was sixty-nine for years. And he worked and he walked from Llangynwyd to Tolmeir, the little colliery just by the side o
f
 Bryn. And - he'd walk from Llangynwyd, I could see him now. After that - anyone would ask him his age, sixty-nine, and sixty-nine my grandfather was for years. Wonderful man. Then after he finished there, he went then - he went to drive a - two horses an
d
 a cart to drive stones to - to other people, some builders, and he would drive them groom the quarry and the name of the quarry was Bryncwnon. It's not far from the main road now where - the paper mills is. But on one - on an August warm Saturday afterno
o
n - he was coming home - after doing his day work, and he collapsed - on the way down, just close by where the spring was, by - Llamaplant. Llamaplant was a public house then, or what we term in those days, tavern, which meant more than a public house. He
 collapsed then, he had an haemorrhage, and an old lady by the name of Mrs Finsbury, she was live - she lived just below me, and her son was the general manager of the collieries in \{BLANK\}
 then. She had been up and she used to go every Saturday afternoon, 
up to the cemetery and place a few flowers on her husband's grave. And on the way back - she happened to see my grandfather sitting by the Toll Well couldn't hardly speak. And she came down right away to our home and said my grandfather had collapsed and 
he'd had an haemorrhage. I always remember a few ambulance people, there was an ambulance brigade then in \{BLANK\}
 and they came up and - put him on a stretcher, and I and my grandfather were very very close. I cried all the way. As we came down - he lived t
hen in Garth, just close by the Garth colliery what they term as County today, and there were two bridges crossing the road - that impressed me and I can always remember that, in fact I can never forget it. As they were carrying my grandfather on the stre
e
t - stretcher, there was a dog on the bridge. When he seen the stretcher he got so excited he fell down - on the stretcher and knocked the stretcher out of their hands. But - the following morning at six o'clock, my grandfather passed away. Now that is th
e story of my grandfather.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How old would you be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 I was then about - nine years of age. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You were great friends with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Great friends. I al - I always since I was a little boy - perhaps I could boast I'm one of the oldest p
eople - in this Valley because - I was - always sat in the big seat with my grandfather. And - perhaps it would be very - interesting for you to know - they used to say in Welsh then - when my father - when my grandfather and the old minister was preachin
g
 and go to what they term in Welsh oh hwyl, fervour, my father would say, thanks be to him, a men. And every time that he'd say it I'd say after him, out loud. And this is what I always remember, the same old lady that - - that - that seen my grandfather 
-
 she always - she came on to me, and she said like - well done my boy, there is a fine deacon for you. And she gave me a shilling. So I can boats - that I've been paid for saying a men, it's gone very quiet and silent in the big seat today, but not then, 
a
nd I was paid a shilling for saying a men and thanks be to him. And - my grandmother - being that I am talking about the chapel, she was the presenter, and - as one that has been a presenter of churches now for many years, I always remember, I can see her
 
now, the old way - the - one of the old deacons was to give a him, they'd read - they'd recite the hymn, then go back to the beginning. Then - he'd recite again the first two lines, we'll take for instance, Here is love like the seas, compassion like the 
f
lood, the pure Prince of Life dying, dying to purchase our life. And as he was - reciting and giving the hymn, and reading, not reading, he knew it on his - memory, out of memory, my grandmother always had her fingers on the seat and she was counting in o
rder to get the right meter. Oh well, that is the tenth meter. Eight - line - eight - eight lines, eight syllables and eight - ten, then my grandmother \{BLANK\}
 and they all sing. There was no organ there then. Yes, yes. And that - and after that - they'd st
op after singing those two lines. The man - one of the old deacons then would go to the third, The pure Prince of Life dying, dying to purchase our life, after that, she - he'd say, then - this is what I say, the difference today, it's quite easy today, t
h
en - my grandmother'd catch up from there on the third line, and the fourth and so forth until the end. I always remember that. That would be - I would be as a presenter now, and my son again is a presenter in Cwm Maesteg, that be the fifth generation. Br
ought up to it. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 She must have been very musical?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, she had a beautiful voice. Yes. And my father was a - beautiful tenor, wonderful tenor. And he used to sing a lot of ballads. And - what we call in Welsh and - my father after he took a great interest \{BLANK\}
 well that was a pleasure more so. During Christmas time - there is what they term a Mari Lwyd. And Mari Lwyd is to be seen now, in St \{BLANK\} And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1514159\charrsid10316288 \endash \{
BLANK\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 YES.. Well of course that goes back to the thirteenth century.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Could you say a little bit of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Now - not - I've tried to find out where - how and - did it come about, how did it originate I cannot find. I've asked - many - many sand good historians and - not one of them can answer me. But - you do know d
on't you what - what it consists of. Of course, yes, the - the Mari Lwyd itself, what I was trying to do, if I could get a little goats head, then they'd place that then - in - in line, so that every - all the flesh would be eaten away. Then from under it
,
 they had a little pole so they could work the jaws back and forth, the teeth and everything would be there. But of course the skeleton of the head - was trimmed with tinsel and ribbons, everything, then there was a big white sheet. Then there'd be a man 
u
nder it, and then another man leading it, Mari Lwyd. Well the way they were doing that they were going around in Llangwynyd village then about six weeks before Christmas. Because they were going to every house, but when they'd come to - there were three p
u
blic houses in Llan then, the White Hart, the Old House and the Corner House. And they'd go then to the door, then they start singing - outside. Well - and it'd go like this. Then, they'd have to repeat from inside, not repeat, they'd have to answer from 
i
nside, but it had to be in rhyme. It had to be in rhyme, well now - and I remember and I - remember it more than once, I used to follow them around the village then, because there'd be a crowd outside to see who would have one, and I've seen them at - out
side the door as much as - threequarters of an hour, or perhaps they were good ones inside. They could - shall I say they could - get these verses back to answer them, in rhyme, and they were - nothing practiced, they hadn't learnt it. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Like an impromptu poetry competition in a way wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, it was. It was. That's what it was. Well really - and the old people could do it. My father - was - a good one on it, yes. And - my mother then you see - in - my grandmother rather, when she wou
ld - take part now and - all at once - a bit of a small bit of poetry would come out a little verse for the occasion, she'd answer that way. It was there naturally you see. And I remember when they were going round, all of them, all the way around the far
ms, everywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And it would start about six weeks before Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Six weeks before Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would there be any money involved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - the farmers would give them - would give them money of course, but they didn't expect anything, 
the - the people were so poor. Some old people - in the houses, they never missed no one. There was no class distinction in that village then. And perhaps one old lady would come out - give a small - what - what we call threepenny bit, a silver one then, 
a
nd - they thought the wonderful of it. But you see after they finish they go back there and giver her perhaps five shillings of what they collected. But anyhow, they were going around these farms. And it was a big festival then. For Christmas. And - if I 
m
ay say about the village then, the people, everyone - all the people then were poor people. Poor - people working. There was quite a number there - they depended on each other, but I want to say this. Social Security - was in - Llangwynyd village before e
v
er it was put on the statute book. Because I always remember - everyone practically had - one or two pigs in the pig stock. The idea of two pigs were - that one would pay for the other. Because the other one then, and it would be about this time of the ye
a
r, end of October, November, that's when it would be. Between that now and December. And of course - I always remember they used to go - the only parts of the pig - were thrown away was the gall bladder - nothing else. Everything was kept. Even - well of 
c
ourse it is a big - it is a big lunch today, in the days gone by, what they call the - well it was in some - the head, the brawn was made of it. And - then - an old gentleman by the name of John Jones used to come round, that was his job, killing pigs. An
d
 when a boy I always remember I was always glad to see that coming. When - of course killing it one day and - it would be hung up just like this now in the kitchen here, because up there in farms, in every house, we had a big hook, and - size it could be 
t
welve to fifteen score. Well, then following day come up what we termed was cutting it up then. Flitches of bacon of course, then that would be placed down for three weeks, salted it. And that would be put - that would be in the cold place. But - there wa
s
 various places - coming from it. My job was, I had my little basket, my mother used to tell me - everybody - every family in that little village then had a piece. But you see somebody else will be killing a pig the following week, the same applies. They 
w
ould - although they were poor there was no one in want. As I just said about social security. I always remember - my mother, she was ill in bed. We - my father, and my brother of course were - working underground, they were miners, And my sister was - a 
s
ervant in a farm just below, she was having half a crown a week, she was having - half past six, seven o'clock in the morning, coming from there at eight, half a crown and a pint of milk. Anyhow, that's what I always remember. Some woman - another old lad
y
 would come - she'd send her daughter. Call at the bottom of the stairs, Mary? Everything had to be ready. The old lady would come in, and she had seven children herself, taking all the clothes, having them washed, ironed them, bringing them back. Then - 
another family would send - one - one of the girls would be old enough. She'd come, scrub the place out, and of course we had no carpets then on the floors, the carpets then were sand. I was sent -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What was it like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Pardon? Oh flags. Yes, yes, s
tone floors. Then I was sent over to a little shop there. And he was - selling - sand, paraffin, bread and sweets. That's right. And - anyhow, go there with a small tin, like a bread tin, go - my mother would tell - tell me now. And after she scrubbed it 
all out - the - the carpet on the floor was sand. Throwing the sand on the floor. Then - the mat - the doormat was - sack, washed, clean, and that was the doormat by the door. And - that was - that was - no more about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How often would you have to get the sand and put it down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh well it all depends how much was usual, - put a tinful of sand, you weren't putting it very thick. But you could hear anybody come you see because the sand was directly under your feet, but that's what it was, that was 
everywhere. Well after that - someone else would come then - we had - there was one big oven, what they called outside oven, I can - take you to the spot now where it is. If you ever go to the village, the old house with the name of Rose Cottage, it's pul
l
ed down now and they've put a few swings there for the children, and outside there, it was my job all us children every Saturday to get some sticks from the wood, and it was placed in this old fashioned oven, and the oven was of course fire brick, built o
f
 fire bricks outside. And - therefore all these sticks were placed in there filled up, and they were lit up and the door closed on it and we had to get clay - to put around the door - excuse me - put around the door and then those sticks had to be burned 
to a cinder. Then - six large loaves were placed in there. And indeed I'd love to have one of those loaves to eat today. Not by machine but they were done by hand.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did you have to take the loaves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, I used to go and fetch 'em, all us child
ren go and fetch them. And all the family, if there were two of you - in the village then - and everyone had to bake on different days. And this - and why I'm saying that this - the social security as we call it - then - there was an old lady there, she k
e
pt a little shop, she was a widow. And she was considered as the nurse. In the village. And - she would come - I always remember - she'd come - how are you today Mary? No one was called there by their surname. But - there were such names as Katherine Hopk
i
n and - Ann, a Governess and so forth, many names, and - they were coming but this lady she was considered the nurse. No training. But she was tender. She was coming to see if - how are you today Mary? Oh, I am better today. And she would bring - I often 
w
ondered - she'd bring a little basin of gruel they called it then. But there was a lovely smell to it. And in that - they - they do tell me, you go downstairs now. And I'd go downstairs - but as I was passing I smelt there was something - there was brandy
 
in the gruel. But - I always remember when I'd go downstairs, after Mrs Davies would have gone, the nurse, she'd call me up, here you are, a little drop for you, and I've have a little drop of this and I knew there was a drop of brandy in it. But mind you
,
 those things were carried on there. And that was week in. Assuming now there was a bereavement. And I think this was wonderful. As I - I want you to remember, everybody was poor in that sense, there was no moneyed people there. But any - and it was poor.
 
And I always remember this. Two of the deacons and one lady would go round every house. But there was no need for them. They'd come to this - to the governess, she - we called her - she was Mrs Evans Cadrawd. Cadrawd was a big his - historian as I suppose
 
you know and heard of, and he was the father of - Gareth Llewellyn, Fred Evans his name was, that wrote a book. And - everyone would go there - no one knowing - where it was coming from, and all the expenses, food everything was paid, no one knew, who gav
e
 it, where it come from, but it was given. Sympathy in action. And that was the life. That was the life. Well perhaps I'd like to tell you a little about the school. I went to Llan school. From - small boy about three or four years of age, little I rememb
e
r of that, but - the governess then was - as I've just said, was Cadrawd's wife. Whenever we see the governess, Mrs Evans, wonderful lady, every boy, whenever we see her, if it was ten times a day, on the road, we'd raise our caps. And - the girls then, s
t
ill children, the girls then, if they'd meet her, they would just - what they call then couchy then. Acknowledge, that means curtsey. Well - that - that one expects, we were taught. Another thing - in the school - Cadrawd - used to come over - twice a wee
k
 to the - to the school, the school is in Llan today. And he used to come over about twice a week in the afternoon, and he used to teach us old ballads. And - I don't remember much of any of them now, but I always used to come. And - we didn't have any co
p
y books. It was slates we had. And a little wooden frame around it. Slate pencils too. And - if we were doing - something and we were good and - paying attention and learning, and I always remember - more than once I was sent home - with my writing on the
 
slate, to show it to my mother, and then come back to school, and I always remember my mother was washing - clothes at the time, and some of the soap had gone on the slate and half of my writing - was washed off, but still - everything was all right, it w
a
s honourable that I should go there, and - of course according to my mother - it was great. And - when I came about - ten years of age, nine and ten years of age, I had passed out for the top class. I'm not going to say it was - very high, but I want to s
a
y this, that great men went to school, not - not referring to myself mind, but there was great people come out from there. Preachers. Historians. Missionaries. Come out from that school. There they had their roots. And then I was transferred - from Llangw
y
nyd to Plas Lewis school, Maesteg, that is in top end of the town. And I had to walk - summer and winter snow or rain, with my little bag, and a little bit of bread and butter in it, couldn't afford more, and perhaps I'd have a ha'penny about - two or thr
ee days in the week. Walk from Llangwnyd village, to Plas Lewis school, Maesteg. That would be about - three and - four miles you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you be on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh there'd be one or two other boys going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Wel
l when I used to walk - from - from the house - about eight o'clock to ten past eight. We used to go down the road then - never come down to what we call Crossing Square, we used to walk up past \{BLANK\}
 and my - my pal there, a schoolboy, I used to call fo
r him, was Gwynn Evans. Reverend - Gwynn Evans. I used to call there at Gellinlaenor farm, right, away we'd go, to Plas Lewis, and the schoolmaster there, wonderful gentleman. Mr William Glover. I can remember him now. Then - after we'd been in - in the f
irst session, out for dinner. We used to go across the road, what is called a tuck shop, Mrs - Mr Cox, Mr and Mrs Cox was keeping that next door to the Castle Hotel. And we used to go in there with our little bit of bread and butter -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Is that all you'd have, bread and butter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Nothing else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No. Perhaps there'd be jam in it sometimes if I didn't have the ha'penny. But my reason for having the ha'penny was - to go - over - to the - this little tuck shop as we called it, and we were ha
ving a ha'porth, not a pennorth, ha'porth of green peas. That was our dinner. When we could afford to have a ha'penny. And if I didn't have a ha'penny my ma - my mother used to put a bit of jam on my bread and butter. And I always remember - assume it wou
l
d come to rain now about three o'clock - well - you boys you'd better go early. And we only had to cross the road, and we used to walk to Maesteg station and - to catch the twenty to four train down. We never said a word. Because we had no money to pay fo
r
 the train. But we used to go in the top end of the of the sta - of the platform and come out the other end and go home, we were delighted were going home early. But - the schoolmaster - I hold him in respect, little he knew that we were going that way, w
e were walking all that way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 He thought you were going in the train?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes. YES. And we - we never asked him but he would come and tell us to go. Mr Glover Maesteg, wonderful man. Then we'd come home same way, but going Gelli Laenor his mother, ar
e you coming. Then, come in and have a glass of milk. Then she'd cut a currant loaf, homemade, piece of that, and a glass of milk. Home I'd get then, and I'd reach home about ten to five. Now - going to Plas Lewis school today - they go in their taxis, or
 bus. School milk. Meals in school. It wasn't then. It wasn't then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you go all the time to school, what would happen if the weather was bad?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh - if it was - out of reason of course. But if it would clear up we'd go. And Mr Glover would understand. Then you - yes - well done boys, you came this morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you miss a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No. No. Because you were asking me now would I miss school a lot. Then I was transferred then to Cwmwellyn school just below here. That opened in 1910. And I 
was transferred from in Plas Lewis school and I was standard six down here. And in standard six I was until I was fourteen years of age. This time of the day I didn't want to come from school, I wanted to stay in school. But - there were what they called 
t
hen labour exams. When you come thirteen years of age, you'd - try this exam, and if you passed this what they term labour exam, that was the title, if you pass it, of course you could leave school then when you were thirteen. Anyhow, I tried that and pas
sed it. But anyhow my mother, yes, you stay in school. I wanted to stay in school. Then - the examination then to pass into the grammar school, they call it now. And that was above Maesteg that's there now, by the old {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}Port Talbot{\*\xmlclose} station. Then I - tried tha
t, thinking that I'd - go then to the school, what they call higher grade. I passed it. I tried the exam and passed it. But - my father said no, come to work underground, you must come to work underground. And three weeks - before I was fourteen my father
 
bought me a shovel size two. Smallest they could have, bought me a mole - moleskin trousers, and a box and jack. The box was for the food of course. The jack was tea or water. Then - I was fourteen on the Wednesday, my father took me to Ton Hir on the Thu
r
sday. And it - one thing impressed me then, the first day - I worked underground. Remember going - in my little white trousers and the horse, they could hardly see me, a little boy, worked with my fathering Ton Hir, near Bryn. A plant it was, it wasn't a 
p
it. Remember going down that day, and course working with my father and my brother. And the only thing I could do more was just mark the trams with chalk then. There I was going with my little shovel and - that day a terrible accident occurred, in Bryn th
e
n, there was a young man, he was the same age as my brother, his name was - Billy Hughes, Willie Hughes we used to call him, and his work was to look after the pumps, there were three pumps on that plant. And the bottom pump, and we were turning in - not 
f
ar from where we were working. But a hue and cry came and I heard it and perhaps I I was a bit nosy naturally that way. I ran out. This accident occurred. This poor youngman, and he was engaged - he was about to get married. Get married, and - I always re
member - he had this accident, terrible accident - it depressed me so much I've never forgotten it. Though - I always remember -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 He died didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, he died, he died on the way home you see. And - he died of course on the way home. Anyhow
, what he was doing, he was - oiling the pump, and he had the oil can in his hand and he - reached over to the other side instead of going around, there was a big cogwheel, and the cogwheel caught - in - just his like - this - his short sleeve here, but i
t
 went and it pulled and pulled it in and pulled his arm off and over this side and his arm went off the other side. I always remember my father coming. And of course I was looking at it of course - with curiosity, and he turned round and he caught me and 
he - give me a boot in the backside, come from here. He didn't want me to see it. And I always remember that, the young man, but - still we kept on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What did you feel about having to leave school like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh, I was - very very annoyed. I very 
near broke my heart. Because I remember there were some - some days - something would go wrong at the colliery, and - there'd be no work, I'd have to go home. I'd run home - change, and I'd go to Cwmwellyn school, and that's true, that's a fact, I'd go to
 this school, into the school and I'd go and sit in the class, I loved it so much. But anyhow - somehow or other - it didn't work out, I'd loved if I'd had the opportunities that young people get today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No. He was a wonderful - he was a wonderful colliery. Never out of work. Never out of work. And - it's a funny thing, he was - really he was a won - he was - shall I say he was a hard working man, but yet - he - used his brains, he had plenty, it 
wasn't a bull at a gate kind of a thing. He had a system on most things and he was there - wherever he worked everybody thought - the world of h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1514159\charrsid10316288 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 m. He'd never be out of work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about your mother, did she have a job before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - 
yes. My mother came - from - Trefgarnowen, Penny Cwm, Pembrokeshire. My mother - she worked - her father was a captain on sea. And during a storm her father was - my mother was not born then, because my mother was born a few months after the - storm at se
a
, and the ship was wrecked and he was drowned. And - during the time and a few months after that - she was born. Well, she had no one. And anyhow she was brought up by her grandfather. And - grandmother. And - in a few - in about two years, two and a half
 
years, they died, both died. Well - she was an orphan. Anyhow, she had - relations in Llangwynyd then, a man by the name of Thomas Morgan. And he was - born in the same place, they knew - they'd been in school together, but very little school my mother ha
d
. Very little English she could speak, and she came up as a servant in Cadrawd. And she always said - and indeed I must say that - Fred - Gareth Llewellyn the writer, he was a - he was an inspector of education in Kent, and his brother then, he was a scho
o
lmaster, two brothers, of course there were two schoolmasters, he was an inspector or education, and the other sister, the - she was off - she went out to South Africa to teach out there. And - my mother always used to boast that she nursed them everyone.
 And I must say this, they never forgot her. Wherever they see her they would thinking of her as their second mother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How old would she have been when she came up here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 About - seventeen and a half to eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes, thirty-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your mother have any jobs after she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh no. No. But - no other jobs, other than what I'm saying, that - what I mean we were so poor, money in the colliery was so bad, there was no minimum wage t
hen. And - she used to go out as I say she was doing a lot of quilting and - so forth, and she could - do anything such as sewing. Because - my new suit, I used to have a new suit every year. But the new suit I had was - after my brother. Because - he wou
l
d after - take to that suit, and she'd do it and she was wonderful - on sewing, my new suit was a suit after my brother, because he was getting well up, such as in music and an organist and he passed his FTSC. From the college. And - that was my new suit.
 
And she was working hard, she had plenty of work because then - of course everything - there was no washing machine then. And - our bath - was then - was a cask sawn in two. What they called a tub. And that was carried in and - there would be after bath i
n there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Where would you bath, what room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh in the kitchen, you had nowhere else to bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How often would you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh every day when you come home from work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How about when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh a little boy - every week. Every week. Once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 When would you have clean clothes to put on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Once a week. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
What happened when your mother went out doing these quilting jobs or mending on a farm, were you small children then, who would look after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh well we were in school - and - she - she'd be back home. By the time my father and my brother come home from work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 In the house in Llan when you were a child how many rooms were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. There were three rooms upstairs and two down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What would they be, bedrooms upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, three bedrooms, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And a kitchen and parlour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, the kitchen, yes, what they called back kitchen - and the other room, well you were going through one room to get into the other. No through passage. Our address was - William and Mary Page, next door to the White Hart, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Llangwynyd{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Village{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And - of course this is I remember again. That Sunday - the Sunday was a great day - when I was a boy now there were no taps, no water, we had t
o carry the water - from what they call village pump. There are a few - tales being written about the village pump. Because there were a great many things - a great many arguments by the village pump. But we - as children then, there was an old lady next 
d
oor to me, they called Mer Mary George. She looked after the church, she was cleaning the church. And - she wore the real Welsh costume always. I can see her now, with that white bonnet. And then - she had - a - flannel - real Welsh flannel - apron, flann
e
l and a red skirt, I could see her now, and always - naily boots. And by the string of her apron there was a key, I'm sure it was about - sixteen, eighteen inches long. That was the key of the church. Always carried it. She couldn't read. She couldn't wri
t
e. But anybody coming up there and asked, well - we've come to see - we'd like to know where so and so's grave was. Where were they living? Oh - now Nantyfyllon in those days were called Spelters. There as no Nantyfyllon. Spelters. My - well it was change
d
 over then from Spelters do you see. And - oh - they were from such and such a such, such a street. What's their names? Well Jenkins. Ah - David it was. David Jenkins? Oh yes, I know. And she'd take 'em to the grave. She knew every - yes. What I mean, and
 
I always remember we children then had to go in - into the churchyard, and she would shout - to get out, that was a sacred ground. We'd go in and she'd - catch in perhaps a bit of a stone and throw it. And the I remember I fell more than once the stone wa
s
 miles away from me, but she said, what is the matter, what - what's happened to you, what have happened to you? Oh, that stone knocked me on the head.. She'd go and she had a big old box. She had buttons, money, peppermints, I don't know what she had in 
it all, and she'd bring - don't say, don't tell your mother, don't tell your mother or father. Here - here - here's a penny for you. And mind we did it several times but nothing touched us. But - that's - and I'm - that's how it was. Well then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did a
nyone else besides your parents, your brother and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No. No. No, there was - there'd be no room for 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No, no, she were - she'd never paid - in fact she was too poor to pay.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
They had nowhere to send it to. It was done as I've just explained, if she was unable to do it - someone would come - that's how they used to live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You did mention that your mother made the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And mended them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would she make everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Everything. All the clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Were any bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
And then - she'd buy - she'd buy the material, there were - old packmen coming around. And I always
 remember the man, they called him William Grim - towards Grimmeadow, he carried a pack, that is, coming round, paying shilling a week. Then she'd get it - and - all of course my shirts were flannel shirts. And I always asked to have the button on - at th
e back. All flannel. Then my mother always used to make 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Make for all of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, until of course - well my brother when he got then - we - you see we shouldn't wear the long trousers until we were fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you ever have second hand clothes, you had your brother's handmedowns?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about your father, would he help to mend the clothes or do anything?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 When would you have new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well, my suit was - my new suit as I term it, 
it was a new suit to me, was on the big meetings of the chapel. And the big meetings were all - once a year of course. Be a great day then. Because I always remember - the old chest of drawers, that we had there. My mother had a little cape, I don't know 
w
hat would you call it now, that is like a wrap over the shoulders, and I can assure you there were hundreds of beads on it, and they were shining like - like pearls. This cape was coming out on the big meeting. And then - they were - she used to wear it a
l
ways - Communion Sunday morning. That's all that cape was always - worn. That is - by today, I've thought of it many times - we as children laughed many times, the cape is coming out this morning again. But I knew it was coming out. And the Communion then
 
was Sunday morning. And the little chapel was full. No bus, no car. Some would have come in their pony and traps, others would walk. But it was a great day. This I want to say. As I just said, there were no water in the houses. It was the pump, the spout 
a
s we used to call it in English, village pump. And then - we boys on a Saturday the children all, I had to carry sufficient water for this old lady next door, and ours, sufficient water - for all day Sunday. There wasn't anything done on Sundays that coul
d
 - that - could be done - on the previous day. To give you an instance. We had to carry sticks on Saturday, not for us ourselves. We had to see to the old people too, that were unable to fetch any. Carry sufficient water, for the - for the Monday, or for 
the Sunday and washing day of course, but everybody had a cask - outside their house, and all the rainwater that was coming down, it was going into those old casks. Those casks were tarred.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 That's what your mother would use on washing day was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Washing day. And - this is always - I remember - on a Saturday - we had a fender as the old fashion as you are aware. The fender was steel, the stand was brass. That was my job on Saturday morning - I had to clean - the fender and stand. Then they were pu
t in a little place under the stair, what we call cupboard under the stairs. And then - my mother would bring me then - an old pot - an old empty pot of jam and she'd put - whiting in it, and then I'd have a brush then and I'd have to put whiting right un
d
er the grate all. So under the grate was all white. Well you'd think you'd put the stand and - no, the fender and stand was not going back on Saturday. My mother then - and father, they had half a wheel of an old truck, an old truck wheel, half, and that 
w
as black leaded of course, that was coming out then for Saturday. Therefore, on Saturday night, Sunday morning, the old half truck wheel was pushed out of the way, the few fender, the fender an stand that was clean Saturday morning. There was no cleaning 
to be Sunday morning. That - that was every Sunday. Every Sunday. Summer and winter, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How did your mother wash then, how did she do the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh, in the tub, in the old dolly and the old rubber. Rubber they call it.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about shoes in those days, where did she buy the shoes for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh - my - great-grandfather was a shoemaker. And - there were a lot of shoes made by hand then. But where we were buying them was in a shop down in the bottom, what they called Pont-ar-rhy-y-cyff, t
hey've changed it's name now, they call it Bottom Town now, Pont-Ar-Ry, y-Cyff, and - there in a shop we'd - there we'd buy our boots. But - however poor we are, there were - I had a pair of shoes - for best. Best shoes they called it then in Welsh. But a
nyhow -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You always had one pair of shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 One pair of shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And then one for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. YES? best shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How often would she buy shoes for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - they would be kept of course and - you see my - great - grandfather, h
e was pretty smart on it you know, and - he'd - sew them you see. But I want to say this, perhaps you'll laugh about this, but it's very - but it's perfectly true - during those days, my - as I told you my great-grandfather now, he was - a - a shoemaker. 
S
hoemaker. And he used to buy his - of course get his leather - and he was living in a little place called Ty Cwmbach, a little cottage right under Llangynyd, I know the spot now. And - my father - when he was a little boy, I heard him say many times, he u
s
ed to go round some of the houses around there, and collect the urine. Early morning. And he used to put the leather in urine. What they used to call in Welsh lleisw. Put the leather there and of course that used to pickle it. But I remember this. The old
 
lady, she was - about eighty-two when she passed away, living in an old cottage, Katherine Hopkin her name was, and down below there was - the place is a factory now, but it was a wool factory. And this old lady, there was a man coming up - with a small m
a
de cart and just a big tub in it, and going round the houses in Llan, and collecting all the urine and emptying it in - into that and they were taking it down to the factory, in order - that is for some - some reason or other, to clean the wool or pickle 
it or something of the wool. Now that's true, I remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your father help your mother at around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - no, he wouldn't - he - he - never used to help shall I say housework. I might as well admit I'm not much better than him i
n that way. But of course you couldn't expect him to do you see, my sisters had come then, but she was - she - she'd get up so early in the morning. She'd never go back to bed. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would he ever wash up, your father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - I don't remember him washing up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about making the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 I don't remember him doing much of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about decorating the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, I remember, we used to decorate of course - inside and outside the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your father do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, what we - majority of the houses then were whitewashed in front.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - now - we had to do - he had to do the repairs himself. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about any improvements to the house, did he do any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well, 
very little was done by the landowner. The householder, the - the householder I should say, because - he was - he was - Court Colman, Llewellyn Court Coleman, surely - what I mean you couldn't expect - much, because five shillings a month the rent was. So
 very little would be done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would your father do anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, he would, oh yes yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You mentioned that you did a lot of little jobs around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes, that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did you all have little jobs, your older brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes. Yes, everyone had their job. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
How long did you go on doing those, all the time you were in school or as well as after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - you see there was - when we moved down from Llangwynyd there was water in the house, there wer
e taps then. That was done away with. Well my sisters then do you see had grown much older, and of course they didn't expect us - because I had started to work underground then. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your brother help you to carry the water? And your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes. Yes, yes, yes, because - there was a lot of water to be carried you see, especially for a washing day see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your sisters have any different jobs to do, you had to do the hearth?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What did your brother have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Wel
l, he'd have to - he - what I mean, when I came you see, very little he done after that because he was considered a great man, because he was a - a musician you see. And - we - they - my parents bought him a piano. Paying pound a month, from Thompson and 
Shackle, Bridgend, and of course - if he had a job to do he'd go and sit by the piano and play a game on the piano and - he'd play the hymn, that my mother liked every time so he'd get out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What did you think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well of course - I 
used to tell him - you were all right, you passed out, it's on me this time again. I - I'll come, I said, I hope I'll be able to play the piano before long. That's how we used to do, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How about your sisters, did they have jobs to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well, 
the older sister she was working down on the farm continually you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember when she was younger, before she went to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well then say - ah well, what I mean to say, she went early when she was about thirteen or fourteen. And s
he worked for years there. No. And - the younger sister - she was a little lady. Oh she was spoilt. And - what I mean, she - I don't like to say it but - everyone of us were more advanced - in education than her because if she said she's not feeling well,
 well - better for you to stay at home. She was spoilt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How did you feel about that? You felt she was spoilt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, we felt that she was spoilt, well we asked the question many time, why was she - excused from any - from any of the little jobs to do. Oh well - it's different now, it's different now, she's weak, and every excuse was made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 That was because she was delicate or something?
