\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your father ever tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No. My mother did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did he ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, he took me - a few times for instance if there was a - a show or something a horse show, he'd take me there, and I was on all the time I wanted a watch. A pocket watch. An
d - I was forever now on a Sunday - I was going to the big seat and I could see the old deacons all - they had the big chains you know and the link. And I - my - I remember my father had a big watch, you could see it I'm sure half a mile away what time it
 
was on it. And - every Sunday I'd ask my father now - would he give me a - his watch to mind now, and - the long guard was on it you know, it was a long chain, you could put it around your neck, and that was doing my - and you know I'm sure I was looking 
a
t the time forever that's seems, I had the watch, I'd do anything to get the watch. And he eventually took me up to Maesteg and bought me a little watch. I thought the world of that little watch. And - you were - you were asking em regarding my - brother 
n
ow. We in those days - in the chapel there was a lot of - work going on. What I mean to say as - what we call quarterly meeting of the Sunday school. I had a decent voice then. I had to sing. And you know, my mother, she couldn't speak English, she couldn
't understand English.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 She didn't speak English at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well very little and it would be half Welsh. And - she recited I can assure you and there were what they called quarterly meeting, every three months in the church. Yes. And - that's what -
 she recited a palms or a chapter - in every one of them - recited one in Welsh, for about twenty-five to thirty years. And - I was then and he - we had what we call a debate in Welsh, where the family are to take part. And - many a - many a - we had to l
earn all that. We had to learn all that. And there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What did you say a dadl was, it's not an argument exactly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes - take for instance now, I remember - I'll give an instance now. There was one what they call, the Mountains of the Bible. And - I
 remember I had colliery. And I - what I mean - and - and everyone of the children then would have a mountain, they'd speak like on behalf, that's what it was. Yes. Yes. Then - in between during the winter in the little chapel, we were doing little one ac
t
 dramas. What I mean to say we were then in those days contributing - then. And I always remember this little chapel, on the big seat there was an old deacon there by the name of - William yoFoel. And he - Evan y Foel, I'm sorry, Evans y Foel, and he was 
a
 carpenter. And he had made a stage - and the big seat was half circle, and he had made the stage now, all the rafters be - numbered, all the - and we were taking - doing this. Well now - there was only one door to go in. Well on the stage, I always remem
b
er - we had - they were lifting the bottom half of the window, and of course nobody could see from outside, and there was a small little vestry outside, that was the anteroom. And there was a step ladder there and the entry into the stage was going from t
h
ere, and on - appearing on the stage of course. Then the exit was the other side. And after we'd - the same thing there again. And curtains of course in front. We were out there and jumping into the garden of the next door house and then around over the w
a
ll and into the vestry again. And that carried on there for years. And - what I mean - and I always remember they wanted to make it a big one then. And we all marched and the minister - he was a wonderful man, great man, he was - the Reverend Davie Morris
. He was an uncle to - Rhys Hopkin Morris QC, the MP, late MP. And short little man, he had a beautiful tenor voice, and I always remember then we were going then in the Town Hall, Maesteg. The {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Crystal{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} cup, I always remember it. That is of course - that was
 a - a - a little cantata now. Well - and I always remember, and I was in front, and I was in taking my part, and I was calling the old communion cup from the prisoner, and marching from Llangwynyd, three and a half miles up to the Town Hall and everyone 
i
n character from Llangynyd village. That's how we were advertising the cantata. The place was full like that. The place was full. Well, what I mean, that went on - for a long time. And I'd - like to say about - the furniture in this little chapel. In fact
 
not long ago the old agent Bryn they asked me would I meet them to give them a little history of Llangwynyd. And I took them into this little chapel. They've had it renovated not long ago. Well the pulpit there was a - very - not like the pulpit you see t
o
day. It was like a witness box. Go round. And there was three little steps to go out to it - go up to it, and the door and you close the door, and there was no room - for two to stand in, get two and they'd have to be very very thin, and I always remember
 
- big meeting, there was - one preacher there, he was - they were staying with my mother then, I always - my mother always kept them, two preachers - starting off Sunday - the next - the other one in the afternoon, then the two would preach in the night. 
F
our sermons on Sunday, four - eight sermons, until I said some of them, in those days, I said, they had - in - religious indigestion I said. But anyhow, that's what it was. And I always remember this man, Doctor Lloyd Morgan, he was minister then of Hope,
 
Pontardulais, and the other little man was - Nicholas - Portmadoc. And he was a short short little man, small little man. Well, Doctor Lloyd Morgan was like a giant. Well anyhow, Doctor Lloyd Morgan preached first, and I was in the big seat, sitting with 
m
y grandfather, well there I sat always, until we moved down. But anyhow - Doctor Lloyd Morgan came down and he said, in Welsh of course, listen Nicholas, there's an odd pulpit here. What is the matter? There is no place to sit down. And the only seat were
 
there were just a six - a six inch plank. That's all, no chair or anything. Morgans bach, don't you understand, that is where you should be speaking - on your feet. You must always give evidence on you feet, not sitting down. That pulpit is not the place 
t
o sit down. I always remember that. And my mother, did you hear that now? Did you hear that now? And I said it impressed me I said. And that's the old place. I always remember and all the deacons there. And this I remember. Imagine this taking place in an
y church today - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 or Wales, imagine it. It was a Communion Sunday morning. And there was a bit of an argument gone between one of the deacons, and - another man who was a member, he wasn't a deacon, but the deacon and the member. I know the both a
re gone - by now. The deacon was William of the Meadow. And he was a very peculiar man, and he'd had a few cross words and an argument over the Bible it was, but it went from one thing to the other, and William James John the other one was. And - anyhow, 
W
illiam Thomas wouldn't talk with him. They were not on speaking terms. The other deacons came to hear of this. And the chairman of the deacons, what they call him - his name was of course Griffith Thomas, he's live - he was living in a farm what they call
 - Cae Beafor, it's on the way to Bridgend see. You passed it on the way up. And - he was called the father. This had come now, William Thomas was not on speaking terms. And the rules and the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10316288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 regulations of the church was this. Everybody had to - on - be on
 speaking terms - before they could take communion. And if they would not shake hands, and make it up - out they'd go. And he - one was a deacon. They always remember this. They were sitting - this night - this morning now - after breaking, Mr Morris came
 
down - and he's standing before - the communion table, and the bread and wine, I could see him now. And he said, well - I can say this in Welsh can't I? Well - brothers and sisters, I have one important matter to put before you. There are two brothers in 
t
his church who do not agree with each other. They are not talking to one another, and as you know, there is a rule in this church that nobody is to partake of the communion who is not on speaking terms and so we must settle the question now. And I always 
r
emember William John, he was sitting in the top seat but one. William Thomas the deacon was by his side in the big seat. And it was William Thomas was the stubborn one. Now Mr Morris called out, William James John. Yes. William James Jones, are you prepar
e
d to shake hands and forgive and forget with William Thomas? He got up and said, I do Mr Morris. This was during the communion. All - the congregation was there. Then he turned - to William Thomas. Very hard nut to crack. William Thomas, are you prepared 
t
o shake hands with William James and to forgive and forget. No answer. William Thomas, are you ready to shake hands and forgive and be brotherly to each other? No answer coming. Then the third time. William Thomas, the third time and remember the last. Ar
e
 you prepared to shake hands? Yes. And I always remember this. The intensity of it. All the place was full, the congregation. Could hear the clock ticking. He asked him the third time. He hesitated then. Somehow - yes. Excuse me. Then he asked. And I can 
s
ee them now, standing each side of the table, communion table, Mr Morris in between. And he asked them to shake hands. And that shaking hands over the communion table. And as they shook their hands, he with his little white hand, holding the two there, cl
osed his eyes and prayed. The intensity of it. Can you see that - happening today? No, because it meant something then - not to be a member of the church. It was uncommon, but it's common today not to be a member.
