\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your father ever look after you when your mother was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well my mother, it isn't often my mother was out. Only chapel. And when she was in chapel that was in the week and all. When she was in chapel we were with her.. It wasn't a case of go, it was a case of come. However, this mi
ght sound old fashioned today, but - I think I can say this about it - I'm thankful for it, by today. Mind - I must admit as a young boy I'd rather be out playing there, in - in Llan, in that village, but I had certain - what they call fellowship in socie
t
y. Some call it society. We had to say our - little verse. And I remember - my first little verse what I was taught, it only consisted of three words. God is love. God is love. Now things - funny I remember things back there - much better than it would be
 
a few years ago. Well - there you are, somebody said, those things that go into the bucket first come out last. But anyhow - yes, but - I remember this - and always remember sitting by the side of my mother, and - I would never say it - I'd never say it -
 
until she'd tell me. And of course they all had said their verses there, she'd turn to me, say your verse now my boy And what I said is instead of God is love, I said, love is God. My mother said, you have made a mistake my boy, you have made a mistake. A
n
d Mr Morris heard it. No, no, Mrs Page, he has not made a mistake at all. Never made a mistake. He's not made a mistake. He's said a great truth. What he said was - he said our God is love and love is God. And another thing I remember about those - meetin
g
s, I just referred to you my grandfather. We were pals. We were friends, wherever my grandfather would be near enough I'd be with him. And - I remember one night, in the night of the winter, and it was what I called - what they called then meeting of Prep
a
ration. What they call a preparation meeting - for the Sunday because the communion was coming Sunday morning. And assuming anybody had - hadn't been to the services - for the last two months, of course, they had to - unless they were ill or - good cause,
 
good reason for of course it would be a different thing, such as - say - any - trouble at home or anything like that. But anyhow, but they had to come, and they were coming to us - I mean they were coming to the - I want my place. I want my place I can re
m
ember. But anyhow this night - and during this night you see our deacons were - they'd say a word, get up and give witnesses now and say something on a sermon they'd had. And anyhow, this night - it was a rough night in the heart of the winter. My grandfa
t
her hadn't come. And he was living just the other side then, in an old thatched cottage. My grandfather wasn't there, and I was worried - that something happened to him. And I told my mother, mam, mam, grandfather has not come. Grandfather had not come. H
u
sh, he will come now No signs of my grandfather coming. Gave a hymn out. Somebody read. Gave another hymn out. And then somebody went on their knees to pray. Then afterwards - gave - it was quiet. Then Mr Morris perhaps just say a word and say that meetin
g
 - meeting was open then, for anyone to take part. But however - I could hear footsteps, coming up the aisle towards the old chapel. And I thought, there's heavy he is - he is walking tonight. I knew his step. I'd heard his step so many times, I knew his 
s
tep. Mum, grandfather is coming. As he came - I can see him now, and used to turn up the aisle now at the - to the door of the little vestry. With that I could hear - he was taking his box and jack out from his pocket, placing them on the widows ill outsi
d
e, opening the door quietly. My grandfather come in to the preparatory meeting - without going to have food, in his working clothes, with the dust - of the colliery, of the mine on his face. And I always remember. Went in, and he brought in a bit of paper
,
 sat on a seat. And during that - his favourite hymn was Oh Great Jesus who but you could die for us. Preparation meeting used to get that. And I could see him now on his knees. And I could see the tears coming down over his cheeks - yes, I said, in the l
a
mplight, I said, they were shining like pearls. Sincerity. In his working clothes. Do you know - we can't get them today in their best clothes. And I was conducting that - not long ago in a festival. And this hymn was to be in it. And I related this - thi
s experience to the congregation. And indeed they repeated and repeated that hymn, and I always remember that. And those are the things - they've left their mark.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Was it only you who were friends with your grandfather, what about your brothers and your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, they were but - my - in fact my brother was named after him but - I was always with him. But you're - asking that question now regarding children. This is what he was. This will give you a true picture of the man. He was always in 
Sunday school, he was a teacher in Sunday school. And do you know what he taught? The Welsh alphabet. There he would have about ten or eighteen children around him, with the alphabet and he's teaching the alphabet. What I mean to say - he wasn't a great l
e
arned man but he taught the alphabet. He taught the alphabet to William Williams, the Reverend William Williams, he taught the alphabet. And if they didn't know the alphabet they never - could never read the book. And he taught us all. So you could - and 
some were on his knees, learn them on his knees, that's the man. So you can picture what a man he was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember what time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 When I moved down here - well in Llan of course - my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 I knew - knew what it was. And go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes. Go. \{BLANK\}
 And then - when I moved down there - that's the time I'd to go down. The mail - was going from Maesteg to Bridgend then, but - \{BLANK\} and the mail was go
ing down at half past eight. And the orders as I had from my mother then, remember to come in when the mail goes down. And as soon as the mail went I'd go. Half past eight. If I was after that, I'd come in and sit down, perhaps I'd be in later some nights
. That's all, look at the clock. Not a word said. No, not a word said. Looking at the clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Who put you to bed, did your mother or anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - when I was too small of course my mother would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember when you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh well - well you see we had to do a lot of things ourselves then because my mother wasn't - very healthy you see. In fact she was years half - paralyzed. But - we were going, \{BLANK\} we were taught to pray too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You had to say your prayers?
