nday. But everything was prepared on Saturday night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You mean you'd have a joint?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, if - well - not often a joint, we had chickens you see. Had chicken and - yes. Or - perhaps other times often we'd have a - piece of the bacon you see boil
ed. And - we - we had to keep a garden, you see cabbage and - and of course we had to go our - we were going then to work on the hay for the farmer during the harvest time, and for that you sew e'd have - we'd have - the privilege and honour of - planting
 a row of potatoes, we had to buy the potatoes mind, but in this field.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 So you'd have your own potatoes?
