\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, we'd have our tea of course. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well my mother - she did make cake you know. She used to make a lot of cake - on the - on the bakestone. On the bakestone. Yes. And she'd make - and it would
 be a big one you see. Then she'd - make sometimes - then the baking day she'd have a little bit of dough left, and she'd make us, I loved that, bara brith. Bara brith, well it was like a big - \{BLANK\}
 And - then she was - she was making - the apples of co
urse. Apples from the trees in the garden you see. Then she'd make - apple tarts, but not on the plates, she'd make it on - on the bakestone, and then - she'd cut it up in squares you know. It was wonderful, beautiful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What would you have to drink in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - a glass of milk. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would she make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, she could. She would make it say - we were going for blackberries, she'd make it then do you see and - gooseberries in the garden you see, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would she bottle fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes, yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Rid she bottle vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No. Because we - we had a - we had a garden, shall I say all the families depended on the bacon, and the barden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You shouldn't buy a lot of meat then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Not a lot of meat no. We couldn't afford it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would she buy meat at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
She'd buy meat now and again you know. Yes, but they would never buy bacon, we always had some you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about pickles, would she make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Not a lot of wone, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 She made doedfaen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh deodgaen, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 She wouldn't make elder wine or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No. No. She - she would do this - my - she would make -
 see, I don't know whether she believed in elderberry, she believed in herbs then you see, well all the old people you know, they could tell you a lot about that, because they were making this here - what I mean simmering it as they do and all that you se
e
. And - this is another thing we always used to have when we were children. At the - the budding of the leaves on trees, and the falling of the leaves - my mother used to have it from the chemist. They were little sweets, what they call brimstone. They we
r
e the shape of just like - now, exactly, but they were yellow. And then she'd give us a spoon - spoonful of treacle that was always - at the beginning of the spring, because they believed in it you see, and at the falling - and at the falling - of the lea
ves. And - there's a lot of people have laughed at that. But surely. \{BLANK\} And - very little. \{BLANK\} They believed as I'm telling you a lot in herbs - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did she make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What did she give you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well, I'll give you an instance now. \{BLANK\}
 And there was one - two old gentlemen there - they were going every year, every spring, and they - I can see the edge now, because I remember us coming home from work one day and this - old man, old David Daniel they used to 
call him, he was a wonderful man on herbs, they believed in herbs you know. And - he said, here's the - healthiest - wealthiest wed - hedge, he said, in this valley. Good gracious, and everybody looked at him. He was saying - the numerous herbs that were 
t
here. And this is how he said, there are many men who have passed here, and died, and the medicine growing in the hedge. And, I remember this. There were a man, there's a man living today. He was - in a farm. Just out - on the way to Margam, Margam mounta
i
n. And - a young boy he was then and of course he had short trousers. And of course it was in the heart of the summer, and he went to sit down. And as he sat down he sat on a snake. Couldn't see I of course. And the snake bit him - bit him here. And of co
u
rse all at once - and he shouted and the farm was just there. The father - put the - the - pony in the trap, galloped all the way for old David Daniel, which was - if he had gone tupper Maesteg to the doctor by the time he'd be gone he'd be gone. And old 
David Daniel came, and - they told him on the way, he took some herbs from the - from the house with him, all at once - then he put some in front of him, laid there, and as he was doing that he cut - without \{BLANK\}
 he cut the wound a little bit for it yo b
leed as much as it can, then he put these - some of these herbs on that, it was drawing all the poi - poison out. That boy, he was one of the strongest men in Llangwnyd village here. You see, they believed in it. Another thing, I told you - I told you abo
u
t - killing the pig, nothing going to waste. Now take for instance the lard. Well now there was thin skin along the lard. They were all melting that up of course and putting it - and that was going into the - put it into the bladder then do you see, that'
s
 what they did. Well now the thin skin around that, and they were keeping that, they were keeping it a little bit moist you see. Well assuming you had a - wound on your finger or - and pretty bad now, they used to cut a piece of that off and put it right 
round the finger. And if there was any of the gathering or - poisonous, septic, when they take that off \{BLANK\}
 Everybody kept that. What I mean to say, a lot - a lot of the things, they were believed in then. Well - therefore as you say my - my mother wasn
't making any wine but I was talking about this diodfaen. Small beer we called it. Well - nettles. Dandelion. All these things are put in it you see. Well it was herbs in a sense. And of course barm in the middle of it isn't it to work it up.
\par 
