\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did you have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Same place, every -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember where you sat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Ye
s, every - my mother was in the same place, my brother and I either side and my two sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
What about when your younger sister was too small to feed herself, who would feed her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 My mother, she'd have me in a high chair you know, in a chair by her side.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 When she was old enough to join in she'd sit then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. Wonderful. Very refined person. She was angelic, she was an angel.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did she show you affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. OH yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 If you had any worries could you shared them with her or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about your father, was he an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, he was an easy person but not of the type of my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did he show you affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 If you had any worries would you share them with him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No, I'd share them all with my mother. To my mother I'd go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh they - they expected us 
to - recognize them of course and recog - and of course - to treat them as parents. As they - as they treat - treated us as children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brother and your sisters in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. When - my m
other was exceptional like that, because - I remember - my brother then because he had taught me - do you know I was - I had a hiding for not singing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Was there any punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh, one hiding I remember having. But I expected another one which I
 will relate now. But this one was - my brother now, he had taught me of course the piano, I knew it and he was teaching the children in school you see. Sunday school of course. And - he had - rubbed me up in the wrong way, let's be candid, possibly I was
 
- look at it now, but him and I, we never had a cross word after or before that. And anyhow - we were in Sunday school and he said to me, remember to sing now. And I thought, who is he talking to? You know? That business you know. He rubbed me the wrong w
a
y you see. So he said - and he said to me - sing now, he said. In front of all the boys, oh you can do it now. Oh it was a - and I didn't. And my father was inside the Sunday school you know. And my grandfather was there. And my grandfather was sitting li
k
e that and you know he had - he always had his walking stick with him then. And he fetched my father, imagine it. And he had told - my brother had told him of course that I wouldn't sing. My father - he come in, I can see him now, sing now, he said, sing.
 
And I did. And he caught - he caught up the stick you know from under my grandfather's chair, and he caught me by the hair now, and he gave a couple of But he never - but he was sorry for that after mind. And - but this is what I was going to say. What I 
mean - that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How did you feel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh I felt a bit cross with him then because I was in the room upstairs see, and I told my mother - he come in, he asked, are you better today? And I would - I turn - turned away from him, I wouldn't talk to him.
 I told him, I'm here because of you. Well, it wasn't my fault,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
But let me tell you this bit now. This is what I was talking about. On January 28th, on January 28th my - my mother was very ill in bed up here. And we were called to her bedside, and - 
she was - passing on. She was passing on. And - laying there, and we were all around the bed. I'll never forget it. I had been to the - to the Rhondda that day. Well, how are you mother? Come to the end. Come to the end of the journey. And then she said, 
a
nd this was on a Saturday afternoon, she said - now I am going. I am going to a country that is better to live in. Remember children to be in chapel tomorrow morning. Goodbye, my children. And - of course, the end, goodbye, my children. Then - of course, 
t
he end - goodbye. Then - funnily, under the clothes, her Bible, the Bible we have now, her Bible was. Her Bible was open. The Lord is my shepherd, I shall not want. And the old Bible, the leaves - were yellow, probably with her tears and - and the handlin
g.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes. They - what I mean to say - at home - they - we were brought up to understand, to especially to appreciate and have - especially old people - to remember that th
ey - to - honour them always, and anything you could do to help them, we were taught as children - to help them, we did a lot of it in the little village. What I mean as I - I think I've - just said, that - there were no taps there, we had to see - we wer
e
 told to go and carry water for old people, they were not allowed to do it. We had to go and see about firewood for them for the week. Anything and - have - when we'd see these old people we had to help them in every way, we were taught to do that, and re
spect them respect old age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What did your parents think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well, very little - we shouldn't swear. We never heard it - at home. Very very rare, we never - I never heard my mother swearing. She was a very very quiet nature, never get exc
ited, never - got excited, but I never heard her swearing. My father, a word or two perhaps could come out when he'd get off the handle at times, but - very little, we were not allowed to use any bad language at home. Or - we were not allowed to, if - any
 complaint would come, but it would not come you see you were so much afraid that anything of that would come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No, not unless we were asked. Unless we were approached and - \{BLANK\}
 And any - anything we received we were always taught to say thank you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 If you did something that your parents disapproved of what would happen?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
It depends entirely what that would be. Because - I remember - being that you are saying that now brings back
 to me - perhaps I shouldn't say this - in that village I had - great delight in the horses, and there were farms around me and - every - after school of course I'd run down to the farm, I delighted to be working, doing something on the farm, something co
n
tinually. And - this farmer - he was living in the village, and he said, well - many times he'd come and I'd go with him and I'd be - dragging a few thorns and branches on - on my back, in order to - if there was any dropped, any in the hedge, especially 
i
n the hay field, I would do a great deal of that. And I always asked well now I wanted a ride on a horse. And he always said that in Welsh of course, you shall a ride, don't you worry about that, you'll have a ride and that would be sufficient, that would
 
be wonderful to me, even if it was - a matter of two years, if I - if I could have a ride on a horse that would be just what I wanted. But anyhow, this farmer, Arthur Edwards who had - spending hours on the farm with him, he never kept his promise. One da
y
 in the summer, he had two big shire horses of course and they'd been moving the hay in the morning, and he had a little pony there. And that little pony in those days they implement what they call a horse rake. That was - supposed - the pony was supposed
 
to go with the horse rake in the afternoon, go on about four o'clock then after tea, they'd carry the hay in. Anyhow, I couldn't see this coming but a friend of mine which is a son of a farmer, he came to me and - and he had a little pony himself. Listen,
 
he said, can't you come for a ride, well I said, I can't come for a ride if I haven't got a horse to ride. That man is living today. Whenever I see him he always - reminds me, do you remember the ride we got. Well anyhow what I did, I went down, I knew th
i
s pony was there. In the stable ready now to go after - after they had their lunch or what they did then, was after dinner. Anyhow, I - I went down, and there was another family there which were great friends with my mother and they a little pony, and I a
s
ked could I borrow the saddle and bridle. Yes, yes, certainly, yes, yes. So I took the saddle and bridle, I - saddled the horse away I went. Went down to call this - young man, a friend of mine, same age we were, and we went all the way from Llangwynyd, m
a
tter of six or seven miles. One of the greatest days in my life. But - I had to come back now to the village. I had to be very careful there because a - hue and cry - somebody's stolen a horse from Mr Walters's farm. No one knew where it was. They'd looke
d
 around everywhere Horse couldn't be found. But I had the pony up as far as Cymer, about six miles - seven miles away. Anyhow I came back now about teatime. So I knew where - the field they were haymaking and the little road, I had to be a very careful th
e
re. So I waited 'til the time when they'd gone now to the farm for tea. While they were on tea I took the pony back to its stable, where I had it, I gave it a little bit of hay and a drop of water, I took the saddle and bridle back to this - old lady who 
w
as very friendly with my mother, and I said, thank you very much Mrs Evans. Everything is all right. I went home. Now then - when I went in my mother wants to know, where have I been? And of course - I always said the truth. It is no good - be no good for
 
me to say a lie. I'd be - I'd come off much better if I said the truth. And I told my mother - what I had done. And I was a bit of a - I was one of the favourites of my mother, so she said, well now - you must be starving, that was her worry. Yes, I said,
 
and I always remember she boil - boiled a duck egg, and I had that and - you go upstairs and go to bed now because there's a - terrible place in - in - in this village that somebody's stolen the horse. Anyway while I was - after - gone - I was upstairs, h
e
re I heard the big knock at the door. They had heard that I was missing from Llan. But of course they - no one said a word. And this farmer, and he was of a very very nasty nature, very vicious man he was. They had the knock at the door and - you can imag
i
ne how I felt when I knew the knocker. My mother went to the door and she said, where is that boy? Where is that boy of yours? Oh he's - upstairs, he's not very well. And retired. Where he he been? Oh I didn't ask him where he'd been. But anyhow - with th
a
t my father had just come home - from - from work, from the mine, and he called out to my mother, who's there Mary? Oh Mr Walters. So he wasn't - he - this farmer was not very well liked in the village. And my father went to the door - and he said - where
 
is that boy of yours? Well you've just been told, he's upstairs. Oh. Now he said, this pony of mine have been missing and I wanted him in the horse brake, he said, and now, he said, I cannot - carry the hay in today, it'll have to be left. Oh yes, well wh
a
t about it the but now my father had asked me what had happened. I told him the truth. Of course - I was afraid of course, what was going to come off. But anyway I listened on top of the stairs what was going on by the door. And he said, well now, he said
,
 if I see him, he said, he'll - he'll know he'll be too sore to sit down once I'll get hold of him. I always remember my father telling him - Mr Walters, he said, don't you lay your hand on that boy. Don't you touch him, or, he said, you'll be sorry for i
t
. And let me tell you, yes, yes, he took the horse. But listen, he said, remember this, never promise a child anything - unless you expect and in - intend keeping your promise. So you had promised that boy, yes, for weeks and months he has worked hard for
 
you just to ride, you've never kept your promise, therefore, he said, go now. What a relief. But anyhow that was my - that's how my parents - if I had said a lie, I would be much worse off. But I said the truth and what would happen, and that's all - that
 is that story.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you ever get a punishment for anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
I don't remember being punished at all. Not that I was an angel by a long way. But - I was - we were always told, we were always checked you see and told what we should do and how we 
should be - talk to people and how we should be - behave. Because I do know, if my father came to know that I had done - something, a great wrong, oh I could expect the belt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 But he didn't give you the belt ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No. No. No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would y
ou say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents, or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well, shall I say I had it from the both. But I've got to admit, my father - my mother did much more of it be
cause she was thinking more as a mother naturally. But she was always always telling us, don't you do this, don't you do that. And of course we had plenty of respect, she demanded our respect - not - that we were - afraid of her, but - she - she was such 
a tender woman and a wonderful mother she was. She demanded our respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well I've got to admit, no. It wouldn't because - I don't say - I don't remember if I'd have a present, pe
rhaps it'd be an orange - or something like that. Take for instance Christmas time. We were so poor then. And of course as you know then it was the custom you hang your stocking. I always remember that - there'd be nothing much in the stocking perhaps the
re'd be a few nuts or an orange, an apple, but to fill the stocking up perhaps there'd be a few cokes to fill it up at the bottom. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What did you think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - we were not - shall I say everybody - all the children in Llan were something similar because poverty was - right through the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 So you wouldn't think anything of it really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No. No. But - I always remember - in the little chapel we were - we'd have a Christmas tree there. And of course there's a small article
 every child was having, however small it was. Well it always was appreciated. And of course as far as - going away to the seaside - very little - never went - until - the Sunday school trip, always remember - brakes for them. There was no buses, no chara
bancs even then, but - horses and - what a wonderful day that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you go every year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Every year, yes, with the Sunday school. Down to Porthcawl or Llantwit Major. And it was a wonderful day out from morning, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you have anything special to eat on your birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you have any guests to tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh dear no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Do you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - I always remember a Christmas Day li
ke this, it was the big day, because I think as we've heard before - it - being that - during that time, just before Christmas we were killing a pig. And - there is what - in the chapel then - there was what they call - they were coming up - there was a s
e
rvice, Pilgin they used to call it in Welsh. And that service was - at half past six, six to half past in the morning, Christmas morning. Everybody had to walk, you'd be surprised, place was full. Old people coming. And I always remember - about three or 
f
our of the old deacons calling - in the morning, and - my mother then - the oven - fire would be going, she'd get up about four or half past four, and these old people were coming up - to have a meal then. And that what she had was - just a little piece o
f
 the pig - just a small little piece of the pig and of course, onions with it and everything - they were coming there. And they'd arrive about half past five or quarter to six. Then - perhaps one of the old - or two of the old deacons would hand me - a th
reepenny bit. And I thought that was wonderful. But apart from that of course we don't remember - I don't remember having any - any big function as they do today, such as birthday party and so forth, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about Christmas Day when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
On the Christmas Day, there was the singing festival. Down in town, all the churches - and of course - we children, we had to - learn - some verses, then mother would take us all the way from Llangwynyd - that would be about two and a half mile
s to this church. No bus. Walking back and forth. And we'd be going down - to the service in the morning. We'd come back, we children wouldn't be going there afternoon, be too much, but - of course we'd have a chicken for - or a duck because we kept them,
 for our Christmas dinner. Then we'd be going with my mother to the evening service, but she'd go in the afternoon again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. My - we had a piano. My - brother was a - much greater and a bigger
 musician than I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
What about when you were children, when you were young in school, did you have a piano then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, we had a piano because he was much older than me. And - I had a violin. And I was taught to play the violin. Played in orches
tras after. And - then I had an oboe as well. Yes. And of course - we went in - in those days you see we - musically we were taught so far. And - of course it meant \{BLANK\}
 as well. But we were taught solfar, very little of solfar you hear today. And - in 
many of the chapels in the vally - the presentor or a conductor would have - then - on a certain night, solfar class. And in those days everybody could read their part. There were - soprano, alto, tenor or bass. They could read their part. And I remember 
a
fterwards - that finished, and I remember going to a night school then, when I started to work. Going to night - night school. Shilling for the term. And then we'd be taught again you see music there but of course I went from there after to another teache
r -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 A music class was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
A music class. Night school. Shilling for the term. And of course when I went to - learn to play the violin I went up to Maesteg to - a gentleman by the name of Mr Lord.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You were older when you started to learn the violin?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, I was about fifteen then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How old were you when you had the oboe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh well, when I was about twenty. Yes, yes. And of course we formed an orchestra then, there were two orchestras in the town, Maesteg. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Was there anyone else who played, your older brother played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about the others in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
My younger sister. She was a - but - rather curious. Put a piece of music in front of her. If you sang it she could play it all. But hardly she could read it but she'd play anything by ear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh my - mother was a - my father was - he had a lovely - a beautiful tenor voice. And he was singing, and he was singing sometimes when he'd go on out and have hi
s drink he'd sing the old ballads and what we call love songs. Down in the public house of course because the public house was then the tavern as I - I think I mentioned before. Now - in that chapel in Llan then - Llangwynyd village - there was - they wer
e
 going, and many of the old deacons would go - and there they'd have a glass of beer and the big discussion would be there would be the sermon from the Sunday. And there'd be a big discussion, but - especially there was one - one there called the Old Hous
e
, it's there now, there was an old lady by the name of Mrs David, she was a widow, if there was a swear word - that's how she'd do. Drink up, will you please drink up, Kings highway. See, go, and had to go. There was no bad language - to be heard there. T
herefore, shall I say they were - gathered together, and yet they thought in this public house this of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Was it the only public house there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh no, there were three there. Yes. There was three - three public house, and the Anglican church, and a - a Welsh Congregationalist church and a Methodist church in that little village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 It was the one particular pub they used to go to was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh no, they used to go to three. Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Was there anyone in the family who sang, your father used to sing tenor?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes, yes. And I sang. YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - sang in concert?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 I mean in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, yes, yes, we would all sing, he'd be playing the piano because - as I - I think I've mentioned before, that - what they call the quarterly meeting, with the Sunday school, and all us had to take part. Well of course I had to sing a solo.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your mother sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No. My mother - was reciting. Because - she - was to commence the service and she would recite the psalm, or a chapter. I mentioned that before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did you ever make music together as a family in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No, I - my brother and I, we - we - composed hymn tunes of course. I composed - he composed them, and he composed anthems and - all that, oh yes, yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You would make music together when you were young now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes. Yes. Yes. He would be playing the piano, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would everybody join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes. Oh yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No I can't say I remember - played any games because - we played the games of course as children you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes. There were books in the house, but - I can assure you - the Bible was on the table than any other book, not that she condemned them, but because - my mother could not - read English.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 She could read Welsh could she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh she could read Welsh, oh yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - the newspaper would come perhaps to one ho
use and that would be - then after they finish with it hand it over then to the next door, that's how we were all having newspapers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would that be regularly? Would you look at it often like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, yes, it would come around of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 One would come to the village would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh there'd be more than one in the village but - perhaps that will be - assuming the paper would come in the morning perhaps - by the time it would reach us it would be the follow - it would be the paper of the previous day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh well I don't - remember much magazines then. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember your mother or your father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, I - my father didn't read much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 He could read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, he could read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 English?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - I'm not going to say he couldn't read a great deal of - of English, but oh he could read Welsh. Oh yes. And my father - and my mother of course, she - because I remember - my mother - couldn't understand you see, she - she couldn't 
read much English, perhaps I'm going on now, when I - when - joined up the Army during 1914/18 - I was in France in then, I used to - I had to have permission - that is to write a letter to my mother in Welsh. And I was very lucky, the Major of that batta
l
ion I was in he was a North Welshman. And - I was allowed to send one letter per month to my mother in Welsh, because of course - as you are aware they had to be censored, and of course this Major now, he was prepared to do it, and I used to send a letter
 in Welsh to my mother. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember seeing your father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, I - I remember seeing him reading. Yes. He - used to read all - of course as I said he - what we call love songs in Welsh and well he naturally had to read t
hem but he - would learn them you see. Ballads. Yes. He would learn them and he knew many - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your mother or father ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well, before - when I had to learn something, say for instance a hymn, my mother
 would read it to me do you see and I'd learn it, see, she'd sit in the chair and I would of course she'd read it to me and I - that's how I learnt. Because - no one was taking part you see with a book in front of them. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did your father ever read out to you like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No, he wouldn't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes. The really first - the funeral I - I remember of course was - naturally now by today my father and mother have passed on, and my brother, but - I'm
 go - I'm going back now to that time I remember. When I was a boy. Now, the funerals to commence with. This is how the custom was then. And I remembered seeing it, little boy of course. And - one thing - wherever it seems to be - there was - very - not v
e
ry - very very seldom they'd have a hearse. Because the hearse they had then was of course was horse drawn. But of course the money, it was poverty then. But what was happening - every funeral - well I can say - yes, ninety-eight of the funerals, unless t
h
ey were private, there were no such thing as gentlemen only. They were all public funerals to commence with. Well the previous night - assuming now - the night before the funeral, all the men, they gathered about - forty, fifty - twenty to thirty, forty, 
f
ifty, they'd go now wherever the - deceased to be buried, wherever the cemetery be, but they were quite - in this valley in Llangwynyd, in this village where I was living. And they would turn out the night before, all the men, get them together, and they'
d
 go up now to Llangywnyd, to fetch the bearer. What I mean by the bearer is what they put the coffin on and they were carrying it on their shoulder. They were having - it was a night out, it was a funeral the night before. And of course I have no need thi
s
 to say - that they were calling in - they were calling in - of course - they'd have to have a drink in one, they'd go from there to the next one, they'd have a drink, then - there they'd bring this - down with them from Llangwynyd and perhaps it had to g
o
 as far as Caeray, and maybe to was coming from Caerav, Garw, that'd be six, seven, eight from Bryn. Over Margam, carrying over the mountain. But - that was the - the - custom that time. The night - well it was carried. Now as I said, if you had - a publi
c
 funeral. Well now, what I mean to say, it's hard to believe. But that was so. Well what I mean - and this is the order that they were walking. All walking. And the immediate family, as mourners, children and all, were walking behind. If they were not too
 
small of course and able to walk, but the mourners and children they were all - coming behind. Well now in front, all men would be together. Behind them then, all the ladies - the women'd be together. The reason for that is, as they were walking - from th
e
 house now, as they leave the house and of course had to sing a hymn by the house and practice see. Then they'd gather and go now all the way. And in front then the undertaker would be walking, and the preacher. Perhaps two or three, it all depends who th
e
 person, the deceased was. And every so often it would be - a hill - and all the men were trying to - all the men of the same height - were walking with the - well they watched that because - they had to be very careful because if the four were not of the
 
same height - the highest of them, he'd be - he had to suffer for it of course, the weight mostly be on him, the others would be swinging on it. Well now, every so often the - the undertaker would turn round. Turn round. Four would turn out. Then as the c
o
ffin would come to them they stopped then, they'd walk - they'd walk and go in front then. You see, everybody was going in turn. Well now - as they'd go along - only the public - I don't remember - perhaps one or two or three, but very very seldom you see
 
what we term as a private - never - in those days - during those years, during that time, never a gentleman only. And I always remember on the way, a matter of about - say half a mile before they reach the cemetery, that is in Llangwynyd because all the v
a
lley then, that's where the cemetery was, in Llangwynyd village. Of course since then there's a cemetery been - in Maesteg, and - I always remember it. They were coming up and half way there was a public house. And the name of the public house was Lamman 
F
lag. Anyhow - and I could see - it's there now, I can see a little wall outside. Well the word would have gone on - that a funeral was coming possibly from Cymer, that'd be ten miles away, and from - Caerav, six, so many miles away - and - when you come t
h
ere now, the preacher'd be with 'em. When they come now they thought, right, right-oh, put the coffin down and - quarter of an hour here. All the glasses'd be outside there, and this old lady, she was the proprietor of that - of this public house and she'
d
 have a big jug of beer. And perhaps a glass, some of the old men of course that were used to it, they'd have a pint. And everybody'd be sitting there. Some would take their pipe out. And have a smoke, for quarter of an hour. And it would be on the minute
.
 And whether they'd finished or not, there was no arguments, never. All at once the undertaker said, right. We go now. And you see all the pints and glasses left there, they'd go to their places. And away again up to Llangwynyd, to the village. As they en
t
er into the village - there was a square. And - the coffin then - the coffin then would a placed down. And all would gather round, women and all. And a hymn would be sung there. Standing there now, and then going down between the two cemeteries and of cou
rse if - if they're taking the deceased into the church of course they come up from the bottom through the aisle. Well all, they'd sing there, I can assure you there was singing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Who would they take into the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Pardon? Well - some would hav
e the ideas - although they were not - church - although they were not members of the church, but they had that idea they want - oh yes, if they want, oh yes, yes. But in those days if you were not a member of the Anglican church - you were not taken into
 the chancel. Because - \{BLANK\}
 if you remember you were a member of the church, of course you were taken into the chancel But this is what I want to say. After singing this hymn, and they would go through two verses, and singing, you could hear the songs, 
the voices, you know, down in the valley. The beautiful song going around, you could hear for a long way around. And of course - wonderful voices then, because there were choirs about. Then after they complete singing there - I remember many times my fath
er had a \{BLANK\}
 and he was going into the church, and then he'd go up the steps into the belfry, to the bells, and there was one bell there - of course which would be rung then, and he'd be - and he'd tie his muffler around the bell - the bell you see, and
 - of course - shall I say muffling the bell, so - when this would be - and it would be - as they would go from the square now right down - and until they would go - if they were not going into the - 'til they go into the cemetery, this bell was tolling m
o
urnfully because of this old muffler - muffler, a red muffler I remember it, he would go round and put it on. And after - until they'd reach the grave. Then the bell would stop. And - of course - you go through the service I've seen them going into a big 
f
ervour. And it was terrible to - and very pleased when a lot of that has gone. There the family all would be there, all in black. And I - and I've experienced - the singing at the graveside, I've experienced it more than once, but I do remember - I - cond
u
cted - he happened to be one of the old deacons, and his request was he wanted them to sing that one at his graveside, and I certainly - conducted that one, that choir, but they knew what to do. They were going round opposite to where the mourners were, t
h
ey were all bothered together. I had my pitch fork, and they sang the anthem, See above the clouds of time, Oh, my soul, see the land. And you - ought to have heard that. And I remember my brother then, he had a - make voice choir, and he - he conducted a
bout three, you see, was a member of a party, they'd sing, a male voice party, they'd sing, After the pilgrimate of life we will have pleasure. And of course it was - it was wonderful. So - that's the way - that's the custom of then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You said it was r
ather monotonous at the graveside and you were rather glad when it finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, the preacher was so long. Yes. And you can imagine what - what it meant for those that were in grief. But - mind - I'm not saying perhaps that we are - going from one e
xtreme now to the other. In that respect. But mind - that's their way of course, of - that's their way of paying respect to the deceased. Well now - another thing I want to say - regarding the funeral. I remember going - with my mother on two occasions. W
e
m - they wanted me - they didn't want me to go to what they call the watchnight service. A watchnight service. And I remember going, and that, of course - last one here was down just below where I live now. But anyhow, going with my mother, all - place wa
s
 full. But there was no one going empty handed. They were going there, and I always remember sitting just close by my mother on a little stool and a chair, and of course in those days the houses were you had one big room. And there - the poor deceased was
 
in his coffin in a corner. With the lid up. And there - we'd go through a form of service, what would be even more so a prayer meeting. And the minister or onr of the deacons would say a word there, there the mourners would be. Then after that, we'd go to
 
the other room and there'd be a cup of tea and a sandwich or two and of course the oatcake. And - but this is the idea of going there, the watchnight service. That is the idea the old people had in their mind, farewell now, goodbye now until we meet again
. And I remember singing. And they were singing and going in a fervour.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would children go usually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 No. No, I - I was - I was very keen and wanted to go. Father said I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What I'd be then about - eleven - to twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 And your mother took you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Why did you want to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - curiosity. That's all - curiosity I think. For the last look. Oh yes, everybody would go round to have the last look. Oh I'd go with my mother of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember a funeral in your own family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes. Oh yes - my grandfather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Who would go to that funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Everyone. All the family, unless they'd be too small to walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What would you wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh, black. Black tie and I remember a 
black cap. I - yes. Black tie. And then - this was another custom - every - oh yes, all - all black. Because - what I mean, people are so good. What I mean to say - it was then you see - no one would - well Mrs So and so \{BLANK\}
 There was sufficient food, 
and they were giving then - towards the little bit they had, and everybody give a little bit it would come a great deal. And perhaps they'd be coll - paying for the suit for about a twelve month. To pay the shopkeeper for the suit, but it would have to be
 black.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 How long would they wear black then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
I - that's the very thing I was going to say now. Then - for the first service, they'd go there, go - go to the chapel, all the mourners then would sit down, while they were in black for six months. After the - yes. Then - if they were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 They wouldn't stand for hymns for anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No, no, no, no, no. No, no. No, sit down for six months. I've seen them, I know families, I've - I've referred to my wife more than once, of a certain family round 
here, they sat down for a twelve month. And of course - another thing I remember, if they were - if they were positioned financially then they'd change from black - into mauve. What they call second mourning. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 That would be at the end of the first six months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
At the - that is - yes, at the end of the first six months. Then of course, if they went to a concert they'd be outstanding. But - in the chapel, they had to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did they go to concerts during the mourning period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh they did 
go to concerts during that, I mean now this was on a Sunday of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 But they would go to entertainments during the mourning period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, yes. Well I mean then of course - what I mean everybody had to go to work the following m
ourning. It isn't often they'd lose their shift, now, they'd go and - and work now early and come out early as we call it you see in order to go to the funeral. Oh yes. Yes. The funeral was a big thing in those days. Oh - some would, but I speak for mysel
f, the close - relation you know, I'm not going to say they would. The grief, it all depends on what I mean on the family you see. But - as a rule generally, no, they wouldn't. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations when you w
ere a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes. During the time, I'm going back to the chapel again, during that time my mother - kept the preachers, of course we had a residential minister, but we had what they term a big meeting. Yearly meeting. And there were two minister
s coming. And of course, my mother put them up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Was there any reason why it was her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well - in - I - all I do know - that she thought that she was doing a great service to the cause, and even to God, that she thought because her idea of a minist
er - was - she had a very very high opinion of a minister. Because I always remember, and she kept them for years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Only her, nobody else would?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No, in that particular time, yes, until she failed. But she kept on going, you imagine now, we were -
 three colliers then, I'm going much older I'm going now because I started to work about fourteen, fifteen, sixteen. And - you imagine now, with three colliers, no bathroom, and I always remember great preachers like Doctor Albert Lewis, Glynn Davis, Pant
a
ge then, and many prominent preachers coming, great men which were - and - many of them. Yes. And - Glynn Davis was an Arch Druid. You see, both people were coming. But this is what I do remember - and there what you call - in the - in their bedroom, wash
 
stands. She would take in the water, very often I'd do it, knock at the door, Mr So and so. Yes. The water is here. They'd wash there. But they wouldn't go and wash afterwards, that is upstairs. They'd go on the little bench we had outside, they'd go and 
p
ut a drop of water, they'd wash their hands and faces, both of them, in the bucket. They were not that way at all. But of course, the generation - they were ministers. And - my other - my mother was from - Pembrokeshire and Pembrokeshire was noted for gre
at respect for a minister.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Once a year you'd have them would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes. And - half yearly. Half yearly. But one preacher be then, and they'd give an address, what they call in Welsh a lecture, on a Saturday night. Be Saturday night, and the Sunda
y, only half yearly. But the big meeting - would commence, all day Sunday, morning, afternoon - and the two of them would preach in the night, that would be four sermons on Sunday, same applies on Monday. I heard my mother saying, I don't remember that, h
e
ard my mother saying that she remembered the big meeting for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday. That'd be - twelve sermons. On the big meeting. But of course they dropped it off the Tuesday, it was Monday, well that is not very many years ago. Not so many. Yes, 
w
ith Sunday, you remember, yes, two preachers. That's it. Well now - and I often remember that. Because I remember one day, you - I'll give you an idea to prove to you what I mean, my mother's opinion of - a minister of church. Doesn't matter if he be the 
v
icar or anyone. And - every month what we had the preparation meeting in Welsh, before the communion, on a Thursday before, and - the minister then was the Reverend David Morris. And perhaps as you know then, his nephew - he was an uncle to Sir Rhys Hpkin
 
Morris, QC, was an Mp for Carmarthern. Well, he would go round the farms, every - once every month, that is to visit the farms right around, and he'd come back to - our house, our home, and - I always remember - of course - a clean out had to be. Yes, the
n
 the sand had to be cleaned that once a month. Of course it had to be cleaned of course every week. Then - the floor had to be washed out, and I always remember - my - eld - my brother, he was saying, in Welsh of course, what is all this fuss about? You c
ould think mum, that one of the Royal Family's coming here. There is, There is. The servant of the King of Kings is calling here today, and I always remember - that's her idea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did she ever take you out visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh yes, I went with my mother man
y times, she'd go and see old people and that, I'd go with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would you visit neighbours or friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well, go to neighbours and - yes, yes, oh yes., yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Who would take you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh my mother. My mother. No, it isn't often 
he'd go, he - if he'd go he'd go on his own. But I - I more so went with my mother more than any of the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
I don't know. Because - they tell me I was a bit more of her fashion than the other one And I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You were much younger than your brother weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes, but there was a sister younger than me. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 But you went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh I went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What happened to the younger sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Oh well, shed be at home, she didn't want to go. But she'd call in the farms
 and - very - very often I would sit in these old farmhouses, I liked it you know. I'd have a glass of milk and a - big piece of - currant loaf of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Were you taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Yes, my - you see, on the latter end, well during - oh my mother 
used to go shopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Would she take you when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, well - some days she would take me - of course all the shopping was done on a Saturday, as much as was done. But - very often I took her down to a little place they call Pont-Ar-R
hyd-Y-Cyff then, but they call it Bottom Llan now, and there we used to buy in of course, you know - everybody - every family had their shop then. And what I mean to say, you could go - and have well - we can't pay you this week, this that and other, ever
y
thing is all right. That was then. And - very often because in years after that, when I was about - thirteen, fourteen, just before I was fourteen years of age, my mother was half - not absolutely paralysed, but half paralysed, but she never missed one se
r
vice. She would go. And - she couldn't walk very far. And the old people used to go then - to Maesteg on a Saturday. And I remember my grandmother going. And she would go, she'd take the basket when it's empty on her arm. And after - going up to Maesteg t
hen, to the town, got the shopping, whatever she had, she used to be coming back with the basket on her head. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Balancing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Yes, yes, oh yes. She had something round you know on top of her head you see and that above. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 You remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Oh yes, I remember that. Yes. Yes. And of course there were people that used to come around then you see selling cockles and - laverbread as they say. They used to come, well they used to come from Penclawdd all the way to Maesteg. Yes, yes, yes. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 They don't come now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
No. No, very little I see now because you see 'em - plenty of them in these market places a lot now don't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well, very very seldom I'd go with my father to
 be candid about it. Very very seldom because he wouldn't be bothered - I think I told you before, I was - very very keen on having a watch, and that - and I wanted him to buy that watch, and very little before I'd go before or after that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Do you remember any outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well we had no outings you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 What about Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 
Well, I'll tell you about in that - here's another custom which you never hear of now. On the Good Friday of course - my mother used to say 
- make you know what they call small beer, made out of nettles and so forth, and she would make now on the bakestone, a cake and it's - the custom, we all used to go up to Margam Mountain, it would be about threequarters of a mile away from there, the mou
n
tain, Margam Mountain now, and that idea to go up there - with some had buns, pop and - up there to the mountain on Good Friday. And a picnic. And I often thought when I came home, well why was that? And the idea behind that was with the old people - beca
use - Jesus, on a Good Friday, went on top of the mountain. Their idea. Modern day might laugh at that, but there was - you could see there was something - some sincerity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid396929 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Were there any other outings like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4345113 WP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4930995\charrsid10316288 Well - yes, the other outing as I 
say, what we call teaparty, or the party in Sunday - the church Sunday school. And - everybody, it didn't matter what church or - and in church, everybody, and I always remember - the minister, short little man, and we were going up now to one of the farm
s
, we were asked to come to one of the farms. Well - we all had to meet by the chapel. Sing a hymn. Well now, this is when we were small children. But the farmers - would come now with what we called them gambo. That was of course a big cart with just rail
i
ngs to it, just like a cart, there was a cart and a gambo, it was for carrying hay. And there would be straw on the bottom of that. So the little children who were unable to walk, they were in the gambo. And then the old people, that - were unable of cour
s
e through age, unable to walk, the trap, pony and traps, a wagonette with - with all the farmers, they were coming, they were in that. The old people were in that. Then we were going up to the mountain and I - often thought of this, to think of it now, th
e
n the preacher be in front, my brother being the conductor by the side of him, then as we go - all the roads through the country, and imagine us singing now - In heaven there will be myriad of saints, and we were singing at the top of our voices, and the 
o
ld people would be in the wagonette and the children in the gambo, and walking up and not a soul listening to us. Oh yes, the only ones that could listen were the sheep and the cows in the fields as we passed on, up into this - to this farm. But some of t
h
e young men would have gone on in front then, they would - have built up what they call a bonfire. And then the - we were made - we'd have two meals. Yes, two meals - a whole day, we were going at ten o'clock in the morning, and we wouldn't come back - th
e
n when there'd be a teaparty that is in the village, what we called - that's all the church were there, then we'd have sports on the field. And of course you had to run - pretty fast, and to win a penny. But it was wonderful. Perhaps the - the first prize
 
