n 1921 strike, I know I'm coming from 1819 now, 1921 strike - that was six months strike. Well then you - we were then, anybody that had a bit of talent - specially my brother, he had a - a little male voice party, and they went up to London, and they had
 
concerts up there, they were there for about - well, about seven or eight months, and - they were the means of collecting about now six thousand pounds. And during those strikes you see, when we're talking about political - I remember the days of course w
h
en I was going with my little basin and spoon when I was going to school - had these strikes you know, going down - to the vestry of a little chapel down here for my pea soup. So - what I mean to say, it was driven into us shall I say - we couldn't help i
t
, from the - the masters and from the - owners of the colliery and so forth, because it was driven into us then. Of course after being through - first world war, two strikes, I think it has left its mark, it's trademark on young peoples mind and I think -
 that is what is - a lot of its gone wrong today.
